caption: This is doubtless one of the best restaurants in the area. Always when I visit this place I am very pleased. They preserve their very high  standard service and the highest level of meals  they give. You always win with this restaurant. Warmly  recommended.

Always a colorful, fun, tasty experience. I take everything on the starter menu to share with the table and by the end I can breath, but there's always room for desert. Cocktails are surprisingly strong & good!

Good food, good service. But no value for the money.

This is easily one of my all-time favorite restaurants in DC. They serve elevated Russian cuisine in a cozy, well-decorated space. They actually just re-opened after being closed for renovations for most of the pandemic, and they also now have a new chef. The food was already great before, but it's somehow now even better. We ordered the blinis with house-cured salmon, herring salad, and pirozhki. Everything was delicious. Social distancing was well implemented. The service, as always, was friendly and attentive. Bonus points for the strong drinks, which our waiter made himself. I hope they start doing the "Skazka" brunch again - I'll be keeping an eye out!
I never knew how much I loved Russian and Georgian food. Wish they still had lengua. But still oh so good. Ambience reminds me of a Russian tea house

The food was good and the waiter really did do a good job of making recommendations. He was friendly as was the other staff. The reviews are correct; the drinks are so strong that they serve them with an extra side of mixer, thankfully, but my one drink cost more than my dinner at $16 per drink. I'd rather have a drinkable drink for less money because until I could add the extra mixer to it, it wasn't drinkable. Just because it's super strong doesn't mean it tastes good. Otherwise, we had a great time.
The place serves big dishes and for reasonable rates. very kind employees. Will visit again.

All service staff are great, friendly and professional…  Unfortunately food is not great for gurmans from former Soviet Union, but probably for locals is more than good! Kievsky Kotlet - ok… Appetizers and entrees do not impress, except russian style cabbage which is great. Blinys are far from ideal… Meat of Russian steak was great, but was much more than well down… Russian Nastoyka - Great! This Mari Vanna is not the best among all Mari Vanns over the world. Although you must understand that the quality of agricultural products in the US does not quite correspond to the understanding of Mediterranian and Eastern Europe peoples. Despite all this, the food can be considered generally acceptable for eastern europe stomachs. :-)

The decor, the ambiance, and service is really world class. What shines, however, is the amazing Russian food. I loved the pickle plate which compliments the variety of vodkas they have. Word to the wise: horse radish vodka is off the charts good!

Wonderful atmosphere and authentic cuisine. Best for light appetizer & specialty drinks as it is highly overpriced and the portions are small (especially for entrees). If you want to get a taste for Russian food, I highly recommend visiting for Sunday brunch. For $30, you get unlimited buffet and mimosas. The buffet menu is the same as most of the regular so the value is excellent.  The good: -Declicous & authentic Russian recipes -Fast & attentive service -call ahead and ask if the accordion is playing to make the experience more entertaining -Infused vodka is worth a try  Just so you know: -Overpriced, best value is only on Sunday brunch -Portions are very, very small -Menu could be more expansive
Excellent food

It’s my first time to try Russian food, and I love it! The two soups are flavorful and appetizing; pork kabobs are moisture and juicy; beef stroganoff is probably my favorite, everything goes so well with the creamy sauce! Oregin is a must try dessert too.  It’s actually the restaurant week menu, I made the reservation before I realized it’s restaurant week, surprise for me! And you can definitely tell the sincere and genuine from the menu and the whole service.  Five stars recommend :)

A waiter made sure our water glasses were never empty. Food came out promptly. Definitely worth a visit.

My second visit with friends. Nice decor and environment!! Great ex-CIS food overall and an ambiance that takes you away from America to Russia or Georgia!!  Desserts seem so-so. We ordered half duck roasted, fish rolls with caviar (fish eggs basically), and the beef stroganoff. All were excellent!!  But...  Waiters all a bit lost. Better if you speak Russian. No Manager or Owner seems to be present.  They undercharged us by 30% by missing our entire bottle of wine and some vodka but when I pointed it out they seemed indifferent and looked at me as if I were stupid to want to pay the honest bill.  It left a bad taste for me. I may still come back for the good food but I felt sad that the Owner or Manager could care less.

Yesterday was my second time visiting Mari Vanna, and my experience was superlative. I became a fan of Russian and Ukrainian cuisine when I traveled in that part of the world earlier this year. While I found the food and service good and solid on my first visit, my second visit ranked as one of the better dinning experiences I've ever had. It was a hot day, with 'real feel' temperatures in the triple digits, and I had been walking around the city for close to 3 hours by the time I came to Mari Vanna's. When I entered, a friendly hostess greeted me and escorted me to a table. While not overcrowded, there were ample people to give the place a nice convivial vibe. Since it was so hot, I ordered okroshka. Okroshka is a cold soup with raw veggies, hard boiled egg and meat in either kefir or kvass, a beverage made from fermented black bread. I chose the kvass version, and it hit the spot perfectly. I also had a cold meat appetizer consisting of salami, jamon and beef tongue with horseradish and super spicy mustard. The main was a branzino with grilled veggies that was out of this world tasty. And the portion size was surprisingly ample. All this was accompanied by a glass of Georgian kindzmarauli wine, and finished with a coffee and a Kiev tort. As good as the food was, the service was equally great. I don't think my water glass ever went longer than a minute before someone came around to refill it, and the waitress's smile and recommendation cinched my ordering dessert. I can't get to Mari Vanna's too frequently, but it is a real treat when I can.

The secret about this place is that it was originally designed by Ginza Project, the most famous restaurant chain of St. Petersburg, Russsia. St. Petersburg is sometimes said to be the food capital of Russia, and no inferior to Moscow anyway, and in St. Petersburg everyone knows if the restaurant belongs to this diverse chain it is excellent both in terms of its unique design and its cuisine. I'm not sure this one is still affiliated with Ginza Project but it retained their fantastic design, their menu and their quality. It is a paradise of what is called Soviet cuisine, that is a mixture of traditional Russian, Soviet Russian (most salads are), and some Georgian/Central Asian. One simply has to try their infusion vodkas, horseradish and pepper being the best.
